Description:
“Los Pinos Declaration Chapoltepek – Making a Decade of Action for Indigenous Languages” includes the “Digital empowerment, language technology and indigenous media” as one of the thematic considerations to preserve and enhance the social use and value of the indigenous languages. This in connection with the impact of the ICT and digital environment in access to information and knowledge. Indigenous languages as a major cultural factor of identity and communication in intercultural codes is a key driver to preserve and revitalize languages in the digital environment. Thus, ICT tools, resources and platforms should point to incorporate mother languages to decrease the dominance of the major languages on Internet by providing opportunities to use them in producing contents and communication processes. 

1.	Intersectoral online education/training programs that incorporate elements of interculturality, historical identity and mother languages to provide a platform for dialogue and thinking around emerging issues (artificial intelligence and inequality in the application of justice / stereotypes and racism on the Internet / gaps of access due to gender and ethnicity / cultural invisibility and narrative hegemonies / denial and restorative justice) that can be a source of inequities and intersectional vulnerability for indigenous and Afro-descendant populations; 
2.	Support the participation of women community communicators in global platforms sponsored and promoted by UNESCO; 
3.	UNESCO/CIESPAL online agenda - Online workshops of different levels of Kichwa - the most spoken indigenous language in Ecuador -. Online seminars on Recommendations on the promotion and use of multilingualism and universal access to cyberspace and UNESCO`s documents "The impact of Disinformation on Indigenous Populations" and "Artificial intelligence focused on indigenous peoples: perspectives from Latin America and the Caribbean".

