Project’s main overall objective 
To strengthen the capacity of teachers in implementing the UNESCO Global Citizenship Education &amp; Education for Sustainable Development (ESD) programs within their respective school community.
Project’s specific objectives and planned activities to achieve expected results
-	Specific objectives:

a)	 Introduce high school students and their teachers to the concepts and principles of UNESCO Global Citizenship Education (GCED) &amp; Education for Sustainable Development ( ESD) programs;
b)	 Enhance participants&#39; knowledge of global issues, diversity, and sustainable development associated with GCED &amp; ESD programs;
c)	 Develop critical thinking, empathy, and communication skills among students and teachers in relation to GCED &amp; ESD programs;
d)	 Empower teachers with the necessary tools and resources to integrate GCED &amp; ESD programs into their teaching &amp; learning practices;
e)	 Foster collaboration and cooperation among selected high schools in secondary cities in Rwanda.

Focus of the workshop
The workshop aimed to provide an overview of the relationships between biodiversity and climate change including:
(a)  The feedbacks of plausible changes in biodiversity on climate characteristics and change;
(b)  Building on scientific as well as indigenous and local knowledge, the workshop then focused onopportunities to meet both climate change and biodiversity related objectives, and on the risks of considering these two issues separately, including:
(c)  The opportunities, challenges and risks of climate change mitigation and adaptation options (e.g., bioenergy and carbon capture and storage and large-scale afforestation, reforestation and ecosystem restoration) for biodiversity, nature’s contributions to people, and the quality of life;
(d)  The impact of biodiversity conservation and sustainable- use practices on greenhouse gas emissions (i.e., climate feedbacks);
(e)   An evaluation of the synergies, trade-offs and effectiveness of policies and governance structures that simultaneously address climate change and biodiversity loss at all scales, including in urban areas;

